sec.p:
Give F to be a class of functions f:χ→R. Two samples X={x1,x2,…xm} and Y={y1,y2,…yn} are drawn form two probability distribution p and q, respectively. The empirical estimation of MMD value is as following [42]:
1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$ MMD[F,p,q]:= \sup_{f\in F}\left(E_{p}[f(x)]-E_{q}[f(y)]\right)  $$ \end{document}MMD[F,p,q]:=supf∈FEp[f(x)]−Eq[f(y)]

As the definition above, if the function class F is rich enough, the value of MMD will be zero if and only if p=q. But a too rich F will lead to that MMD differs from zero for most finite sample estimates. Thus some restrictions ought to be placed on the function class. One trade-off way is to set F as the unit ball in a universal reproducing kernel Hilbert space H, defined on the compact metric space χ. Since H is a complete inner product space of functions f:χ→R, the function mapping f→f(x) can be expressed as an inner product via f(x)=〈f,ϕ(x)〉H,where ϕ:χ→H is the feature space map from x to H. Then MMD can be rewritten as:
3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$ {{}\begin{aligned} MMD[F,p,q]&= \sup_{\left \| f \right \|_{H}\leq 1}E_{p}[f(x)]-E_{q}[f(y)]\\ &=\sup_{\left \| f \right \|_{H}\leq 1}E_{p}\left[\left \langle f,\phi (x) \right \rangle_{H}\right]-E_{q} \left[\left \langle f,\phi (y) \right \rangle_{H} \right]\\ &=\sup_{\left \| f \right \|_{H}\leq 1}\left \langle \mu_{p}- \mu_{q}, f\right \rangle_{H}\\ &=\left \| \mu_{p}- \mu_{q} \right \|_{H} \end{aligned}}  $$ \end{document}MMD[F,p,q]=supfH≤1Ep[f(x)]−Eq[f(y)]=supfH≤1Epf,ϕ(x)H−Eqf,ϕ(y)H=supfH≤1μp−μq,fH=μp−μqH

Then we can calculate like the following function:
4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document} $$ \begin{aligned} MMD^{2}&=\left \langle \mu_{p}- \mu_{q},\mu_{p}- \mu_{q} \right \rangle_{H}\\ &=\left \langle \mu_{p},\mu_{p} \right \rangle_{H}+\left \langle \mu_{q},\mu_{q} \right \rangle_{H}-2\left \langle \mu_{p},\mu_{q} \right \rangle_{H}\\ &=E_{p}\left \langle \phi (x),\phi (x^{\prime}) \right \rangle_{H}+E_{p}\left \langle \phi (y),\phi (y^{\prime}) \right \rangle_{H}\\ &\quad-2E_{p,q}\left \langle \phi (x),\phi (y) \right \rangle_{H} \end{aligned}  $$ \end{document}MMD2=μp−μq,μp−μqH=μp,μpH+μq,μqH−2μp,μqH=Epϕ(x),ϕ(x′)H+Epϕ(y),ϕ(y′)H−2Ep,qϕ(x),ϕ(y)H

As the inner product can be replaced by Gaussian kernel k(x,x′)=exp(−∥x−x′∥2/(2σ2)),the value of MMD2 can be figured out as:
